{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522301"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:43:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:43:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13819"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13819"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.06,0.13,0.03,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6436"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49006"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6436"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13819"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34024"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7894"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12712"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12713"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49006"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with her new carer, who is concerned about a red patch on her face. She has just moved to the State and her medical history is still being transferred. The patient is non-verbal due to an intellectual disability. On examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 72/min, blood pressure 118/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is a well-demarcated, red-purple patch covering her left cheek and extending down her neck (Image). The lesion blanches with pressure, is non-tender and feels slightly warm to touch. There are no signs of pruritus or bruises elsewhere on her face or neck.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amelanotic melanoma","Non-accidental injury","Strawberry naevus","Cellulitis","Port-wine stain"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe description in the stem is most consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Eport-wine stain\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as congenital capillary vascular malformation). Port-wine stains are present at birth and persist throughout life to either fade over time, thicken or become darker in colour. They are unilateral and sharply demarcated, appearing as dark red to purple patches. The lesions blanch with pressure and may feel slightly warm due to increased blood flow. It is usually benign but can be associated with rare syndromes such as Proteus syndrome or Sturge-Weber syndrome or in certain areas may cause pressure (such as the eye leading to glaucoma).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmelanotic melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an unlikely diagnosis in this case. While amelanotic melanomas can present as skin-coloured, red or pink patches, they are typically not present from birth and do not blanch with pressure. They also tend to be asymmetrical, have irregular borders, and may have areas of ulceration or bleeding which is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lack of other signs of trauma makes \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-accidental injury\u003C/strong\u003E unlikely in this case. While it is important to always consider abuse, especially in a vulnerable patient, the lack of pain on palpation makes it less likely and bruising would likely have more complex colours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Estrawberry naevus\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as a superficial infantile haemangioma, would be an unlikely diagnosis in a 33-year-old as they tend to have involuted by this age. These lesions typically appear in the first few weeks of life, grow rapidly, and then involute during early childhood. They are also more raised and compressible than port-wine stains.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute bacterial skin infection that presents with erythema, warmth, tenderness, and often systemic symptoms such as fever. Whilst it is also warm to touch, the well-demarcated nature of the lesion, lack of tenderness, and absence of systemic symptoms make cellulitis an unlikely diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Port-wine stains are congenital vascular malformations that persist throughout life and may darken or thicken over time.","Port-wine stains are diagnosed clinically and do not require biopsy for confirmation."],"references":["Ngan V. Capillary vascular malformation.  In: Dermnet NZ [online]. 2014. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/capillary-vascular-malformation","Port Wine Stain. In: British Association of Dermatology. 2016. Available at: https://www.bad.org.uk/pils/port-wine-stain/","Nguyen V, Hochman M, Mihm MC Jr, Nelson JS, Tan W. The Pathogenesis of Port Wine Stain and Sturge Weber Syndrome: Complex Interactions between Genetic Alterations and Aberrant MAPK and PI3K Activation. Int J Mol Sci. 2019 May 7;20(9):2243. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6539103/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34024"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13819"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20766"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20766"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/FP2pI9ZiRqSR6NW5vm50WUtLFndyz9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/FP2pI9ZiRqSR6NW5vm50WUtLFndyz9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":1024}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34024"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-22T12:13:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-11T10:19:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6436"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49006"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type"